{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_circle_ver01/data/sn85053043/0051717841A/1938010701/0643.xml":{"full_text":"The Glacier County Chief\nEntered as 2nd daM matter\nJuly 15, 1931 at the poatoffice at\nBrowning, Mont., under the act of\nMarch 3, 1879.\nSubscription 82.00 year to advance\nJACK DUNCAN\nEditor and Publisher\nA weekly newspaper published every\nFriday at Browning, Glaeier County,\nThe Low Down\nFrom Hickory Grove\n1 just been readin' iiiwut what it\nis costin'to keep I nele Sambo in\nbusiness, and my word, it woke me\nout of my sno< z\u2022. The feller who\nmade the figures, he says it is cost\ning eaeh family in the I S., 160\ndollar.- a year, just for Sambo\u2019s\nnormal stuff\u2014not includin\u2019 relief,\nand 1 got out my own pencil, and\nit is 14 dollars a month out of my\nown Jeans\u2014three and a half a week.\nWow, that\u2019s money.\nI guess I sure been a sucker hs\ntenin \u2019to all this sweet stuff 1 been\nswallowing whole \u2014and not pryin\u2019\ninto details or lookin\u2019 under the\nblankets and find who is there, and\ngettin\u2019 the money.\nBut a neighbor, he says, Jo, you\nare just the kind of a duck who is\nto blame. He says also, nobody is\never goin\u2019 to slow down Sambo, till\nwe vote and pay on the sama day.\nHe says, if people dug up the cash\non election day, we would not see\nso much tomfoolery, and so many\n10 thousand dollar Govt, fellers\nridin n in automobiles longer than\nyour own old wreck.\nThis neighbor guy\u2014he is a pretty\nsmart feller.\nYours, with the low down,\nJO SERRA\nSTOP THE \"RECESSION\u201d\nThe hopes that were held out dur\ning the first half of this year for\ncontinued expansion of industrial\nproduction, growth of private em\nployment, and an increasing nation\nal income, have been dissipated.\nThe United States enters the new\nyear under the cloud of a critical\nbusiness recession. I\nThe values of securities depreciat-1\ned by more than 40 per cent in a\nsingle week during October \u2014and\ntney are still hovering near the\nlows reached at that time. The un\nemployment totals, notably in the\nheavy industries, are soaring ser\nously. Toe standard indices of bus\niness activity have shown alarming\nand continued d rope. Frightened\ninvestors reveal an increasing disin\nclination to place their money in\nproductive enterprise. Individuals,\u2019\nworried as to the future, are cutting\nth>-ir personal buying to the limit, I\nwith the resultant depressive tn-'\nfluence on the entire business\nstructure. The chaotic labor situa\ntion is still another barrier to the\nnormal progress of trade and in\ndustry.\nThis recession cannot lie accur\nately compared to the occasional\ndeclines which characterize almost\nall upword business cycles. It is,\ninstead, the inevitable result of a\nlong series of deliberate acts which\ncould culminate only in what we\nwitness today. Those whose voice\nwere disregarded for many years,\nbecause they refused to view condi\ntions through rose-colored glasses,\nare seeing their old prophecies and\ntheir fears come true today.\nThe federal government has pur-\nMieda policy of competition with\nprivate busiaessea, which has pre\nvented the spending of billions of\nprivate capital.\nThe federal government has pur\nsued a fiscal policy which, long\nenough continued, must end in\nbankruptcy\u2014and has continually\nput off the day of reckoning. Some\ntwo dollars have lieen spent for\nevery dollar received in tax reven\nues. The federal debt has been\ndoubled in about five years. And the\nburden of present heavy taxes,\nplus the prospect of still heavier\ntaxes in the future, has l-een one of\nthe most dampening of all influences\nthat retard investment and ioduslial\ndevelopment.\nThe federal, as well as many of\nthe state governments, has hamp\nered normal competition in the\nfield of retail trade, to the end that\nprices have been artificially forced\nupward, and the consumer rebelled.\nBusiness has been burdened with\nspecial taxes which, while small re\nvenue producers, disrupt normal\nindustrial operations, prevent the\ncreation of the financial surpluses\nwhich are essential safeguards\nagainst bad times, and discourage\nexpansion.\nIn brief, government has tended\nin late year* to be the enemy, not\nthe ally, of legitimate business \u2014a\nsubsidised competitor, not an um\npire, io affairs that belong properly\nin the sphere at private enterprise\nin a democratic nation,\nThe industrial and agricultural\nresources of this country are greater\nthan ever. We lead the world in na-\ntional wealth, in living standarda\nin opportunity, and in potential j\nachievment for the betterment of 1\nthe lot of all. Out of thia can come;\na finer civilization than the world\nhas ever known \u2014if only used to the i\nfullest advantage the tools we have.\nAnd in securing this, the first es\nsential is fairness and tolerance \u2014on\nthe part of industry, of government,\nof laboi, and of all other elements\nin our national life.\nCongress has committed itself to\nthe building up of a navy which\nwill compare favorably with the\nnavies of the rest of the world, and\nwork along that line will go forward,\nthough not by leaps and bounds,\nsince the program under considera\ntion will stretch out over a number\nof years. A billion dollars is sug\ngested as the necessarynppropriaiion\nfor the coming year, and that\nshould be a good sized drop in the\nbucket. Then there is the Farm Bill,\nupon which accord is promised\nwithin ten days after the first bang\nof the gavel. Along this line it\nshould be recalled that the Senate\nand the House have their own se\nparate notions, which will have to\nbe reconciled in conference. The\nFederal courts will get continued\nCongressional attention, it is said:\nnot because they are suspected of\nneeding what is commonly known\nas \"investigating\u2019\u2019, but because, due\nto press of business, cases sometimes\nare a little too long in receiving a\ndecision. As some wise man re\nmarked: \"Justice delayed is justice\ndenied.\u201d\nJapan is faced with a growing\nboycott of her goods ir. this coun\ntry, the movement living confined\nto small articles marked \"Made in\nJapan.\u2019, Experts state that if a real\nand effective boycott is desired, it\nmight well be directed toward silk,\nsince the United States absorbs 85\nper cent of Japan\u2019s raw silk. Leav\ning open the question as to whether\n\u0964or not we should step on Japan by\nmeans of a boycott, one reason for\nit seems to be that many do not like\nto see the Chinese crowded too\nbard. Back of that is the sinking\nof the American gunboat, an inci\ndent that has been smoothed over\nbut by no means sit: 1 d. The gun\nboat affair certainly did not pro\nmote good will, without which in\nternational trade can not thrive. In\nthis connection, it is noted that the\nFinns are keeping up their war\ndebt payments, and iheir trade with\nus has increased. The intangible\nI thing called good will has a money\nvalue in business, hi her at the\ncountry store or between nations\nJapan may yet find that she has\nmade a mistake in setting so .mill\na value upon it.\n\u2666VHEIV!\nLandlady\u2014Hercules had wonder\nful strength, of course, but\u2014\nBoarder\u2014But he would have been\noutclassed by this butter and coffee\nif he had tackled them.\nIN STYLE\nsis A WjH\n\"I\u2019m a man of few words.\u201d\n\"Same here, I\u2019m married, too.\u201d\nOR A YOWL\nMr. B.\u2014What was the first thing\nthat struck you when you entered\nthe nursery?\nNurse\u2014A spitball, I think.\nla England's Wassail Bowls\nBrswsd in England's Yuletide\nwassail bowls are baked apples, hot\nale seaeoned with spice, orange\nJuice end rind end whipped eves\nYOU SAID IT, BIG BOYI\nn look/ t\nbeen Raisin Gt\nX X //J\nIS CAPITAL ON STRIKE?\nAs business drifts further down\nward and unemployment increases\nthere is beard time and again the\nreport that \u201ccapital is on strike.\u201d\nThis, if true, would mean that those\nwho have money to invest are not\ninvesting.\nCommon sense alone answers\nthat. People who have money ac\ncumulated it by making each dol\nlar they had earn another dollar.\nThey seek profit ard risk their\nprincipal on the chance of making\nthe profit. And until human nature\nhas been completely legislated out\nof existence, there will be no \"strike\nof capital\u2019\u2019 so long as that capital is\ngiven the opportunity to flow in le\ngitimate investment.\nWhat is wrong with investment\nmoneys then out of which comes ex\npansions and more employment?\nHave you ever heard the story of\nNellie, the Beautiful Cloak Model,\nand the Villian?\nIn the first chapter, the Villian\ntied Nellie to the railroad track. In\nthe second chapter he beat her up.\nIn the third he threw her in front\nof a buzz saw And in last chapter\nclimax he asked, \"Nellie, why\ndon\u2019t you trust me?\u2019\u2019\nGovernment spending will c ime\nin fc r a thorough review, followed\nin all probability by proper action.\nThe Administration hopes to cut\nexpenditures along that line about\na billion dollars compared with last\nyear. To this there will be some op\nposition since there exists a respect\nable group which believes that the\npurse strings should remain loose a\nlittle longer, in order to tide over\nwhat is politely called the business\nrecession.\nthe YEAR Old M\n\u201cand New\ne By Philander Johnson\nin the Washington Star\nIJAPPY NEK YEAR comes to view.\nH I'll say \u201cHappy Old Year!\" 100.\nSince a share of happiness\nhies in memories we possess.\nOld year, we cannot for net\nDuties that were bravely met.\nNor the courage that was taught\nH hen the hours with doubt were fraught.\nOld year, 'mid the shades of guilt\nYou have offered many a smile,\nLike the sunshine, clear and warm,\nThat must conquer every storm,\nHe the future what it may,\nPioneers have shown the way.\nHappy New Year comes to view\u2014\nI'll say \u201cHuppy Old Year!*' too.\nStorm Sash and Doors Save Fuel\nMake Your Home Warm and Tight For Winter\nMost homes need storm doors and windows for winter\nas much as screens in summer.\nCold air packed against the outside of the window\nchills the glass and lowers the temperature in the\nvicinity of the window from 10 to 15 degrees, Storm\nsash forms a dead air space between the two glasses\nwhich serves as a blanket of insulation between the\noutside cold and the warmth of the room.\nWe have a very complete stock of storm doors and\nwindows, and cap deliver promptly.\nSherburne Lumber Co.\nEARL CARPENTER. Yard Msnsgsr.\nBrowning, Montana\nJwo New Year's\nOrgan Hunters\na\nY LUELLA B.LVOHS\n.g,\nANN HUDSON hadn\u2019t recovered\nfrom the shock of the firsl\nChristmas present her hus\nband, Phil, had given her, theii\nfirst holiday together. Hadn\u2019t she\nalways dreamed of receiving a nice\ncar or a fur coat, or something\nequally as nice? But he had laid\njust a fifty-cent piece at her plate\nChristmas morning. All he coulo\nafford just now. he said.\n\"Ann, dear, get on your wraps,\ndig out the fifty-cent piece and let\u2019s\nspend New Year\u2019s day by attend\ning Hartman\u2019s farm sale just north\nof Morton City, today,\u201d he urged.\n\"You know Frank Hartman had\nsome grand antiques and maybe\nyou can make that fifty cents pay\ninterest by investing it.\u201d He loved\nto tease her.\nEveryone in Fletcher and Putnam\ncounties had had the same idea\nand by the time the Hudsons\nreached the Hartman farm Ann\nhad quit being heartbroken and\ndisappointed over her insignificant\ngift.\n\"There\u2019s one tiring, they won\u2019t be\nable to give away here,\u201d a neigh\nbor told Ann. \"That\u2019s that pair\nof old reed organs over yonder. One\nbelonged to Mrs. Hartman and the\nother to her Ma before her. No\none will so much as carry an organ\nhome these days!\u201d\nThat set Ann wondering, but when\nPhil started the truck homeward, I\nhe was the one who was wonder\ning. \"You always know best, hon\ney, but won\u2019t you let me in on the\nsecret? Why the two organs at\ntwo bits each, please?\u201d\n\u201cJust to tease, I\u2019m not telling,\nbut you must admit I got a lot of\nmusic for four bits, Phil.\u201d\n{Spring displaced the winter and\nalong came the summer and with it\na round of county and state fairs, I\nexhibits and the like. And when the I\nprize lists were being published, one\nitem stood out like a sore thumb\u2014\n\"Extra classification\u2014Antique reecf i\norgans\u2014oldest and finest group I\ndisplay: First, second and third I\nprizes, Mrs. Phil Hudson\u2014s3o.oo.\"\nThat was a sample of the prizes 1\nAnn collected throughout that Bum\nmer and she and Phil attended\nfarm sales everywhere, hunting\nrare old reed organs which Ann\ntinkered with, polished, mended,\nplayed and finally exhibited, dates\nand fill. She had started something,\nfor others were delving into the or\ngan collecting hobby.\nNaw Year's morntag \"Totti\naround again and Phil found tiny\nAnn and Phil Attended Farm Sales\nHunting Old Organa.\nenvelope at his plate. \u201cJust a little\ngift and a little interest on that\nfour-bit investment you financed\nlast year. Let\u2019a hunt up a farm\nsale to celebrate the day, too, Phil.\nWhat say?\u201d\n\u201cSure, but it\u2019s 82 miles away so\nwe'd better get going. What\u2019s 82\nmiles in the lives of two organ\nhunters?\u201d he gibed back.\nWestern Newspaper Union.\nG. G. K I P P\nUee os for year\nWOOD AND COAL\nBrowning. Montana\nLaundry Laundry\nDry Cleaning\nDrop us a line or phone Cut Bank and we\u2019ll look you up.\nLadies DRESSES SI.OO Mens Suits SI.OO\nfXy Overcoats SI.OO-$1.25\ndresses T 51.Z0 Ti e s Cleaned sl.lO dz.\nHats Cleaned and Blocked 1.00\nLEAVE BUNDLES AT GAMBLE STORE\nU. S. Laundry and Dry Cleaning\nTrips to Browning Mondays and Thursdays\nCUTBANK We Deliver and Pickup PHONE 10\nIT\u2019S HERE TO SAVE YOU MONEY\nThe Most Beautiful Car\nDodge Ever Built\nTHE BIG 1938 DODGE\nThe \u201cAMERICAN BEAUTY\u201d\n47 privre\u2019riv* nev improvement.! Distinguished new\nbeauti! New \"Simplified Driving\u201d control!. Elegant\nnew \"Lustre Lounge\u201d interim! 1938 \"Silenced Airglide\nRid.! Greater driving urotection! Plus the amas.ing\nmoney-saving features that have led 142,525 people to switch\nfrom other rars to DODGE in the year!\nNOW ON DISPLAY AT\nMcDougall motors\nBROWNING, MONT.\nTURF CIGAR STORE\nD. f. HAOEHW, Prop.\nPocket Billiards Cirars Tobaccos\nThe Meeting Place of the People of Browning\nYour Patronage Solicited\nThe Finest Meats\nThe market affords esn be obtained at all times\nfrom our stock of Fresh and Cured Meats, Fish end\nChickens. Beef from the best grain fed Steers. Lun\ncheon Meats of the very best. Fresh Fish every week.\nSee us for the Best in Meats\nA Trial is All We Ask!\nCash Meat Market\n4PUPS MHDgABDT. fwawr\nNotice\nDr, oo>d Davis, of C. E. Davis\nSons, Great Falls, will be j.\nBrowning fitting glasses on Sy\nurday, Jan. 22nd, at the Yegen\nHotel.\nJAMES E. BURDETT\nAttorney-at-Law\nOffice: Hagerty Hotel bldg.\nPhone 44 Browning, Mont,\nTOM HAMBY\nDealer in\nCoal Wood, and Fuel Oil\nPhone 79 Office: In forme\nMonarch Lumber Co.\nBrowning, Montana\nBROWNING FUNERAL HONE\nLEIGH KERR\nFuneral Director\nCOMPLETE FUNERAL SERVICE\nCalls Handled from Local Sri\nOutside Hospitals.\nHom No. 31 Browning, Not","height":"20964","width":"13836"}}
